> From: kim@Athena.MIT.EDU
> Date: Fri, 13 Aug 93 19:05:37 EDT

> Thanks for the info. If they can/do stick around those numbers look 
> fine.

> As far as Matt goes, I don't think he can be a urop because he graduated. 
> I believe Jonathon will be working for Tim as a full time staff member.

Non-undergrads can work for us, they just can't be UROPed.  This means that 
if we choose to hire them we have to pay overhead (39%) on their hours.  

Students in the new Course 6 5 year program do not usually receive their 
undergraduate degree until the end of year 5, therefor they can be UROPed 
all 5 years (at least that's what the UROP office said last year -- we'll 
find out this fall with Chris Cotton.)

> Here's an interesting question though: do we need to make sure
> salaries are somewhat consistent across IS? For example, I know
> that Matt also works for CSS and I don't think he makes nearly
> as much as he does in DCNS. Is this something we should be
> paying attention to?

I don't think that we need to make student salaries consistent across IS.  
I think that watchmakers have different responsibilities and require 
different skills (e.g. more development experience) than support positions 
in CSS & NSS.  (I don't know what NSS pays help desk students, or plans to 
pay resnet students, but I suspect it is less than we pay watchmakers).  
While we pay our student developers more than many on campus jobs, we also 
pay less than some local companies which also compete with us to hire 
student developers.

I think our student salary rates are about right.  Occasionally students do 
reject our job offer or don't continue working with us because they can 
make more elsewhere.  So I don't think we are paying much too much.

I would be interested in what other people think.  Do we pay too much, too 
little, give too many raises, too few, etc.?

- Mark
