	Hi,

	I have received a proposal from Mark Montague about the undelete
feature for the ext2 fs.  Mark is interested in working on it and he'd like
to get some feedback on his proposal from other developpers.  So I have
forwarded this mail to you.

	I have not read Mark's mail very carefully yet.  As soon as I read it
(this evening I think), I will send my comments to him with a copy for you.
On your side, if you have any comments, please send them to Mark with a copy
to me.

	Thanks,

		Remy

Forwarded message:
> From plph@umcc.umich.edu Sun Aug 15 08:43:47 1993
> Message-Id: <m0oRbnO-000A9AC@umcc.umich.edu>
> From: plph@umcc.umich.edu (Mark Montague)
> Subject: ext2 undelete proposal
> To: card@masi.ibp.fr
> Date: Sun, 15 Aug 1993 02:42:25 -0400 (EDT)
> X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL22]
> Mime-Version: 1.0
> Content-Type: text/plain; charset=US-ASCII
> Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
> Content-Length: 10651
> X-Lines: 242
> 
> 
> PLEASE FORWARD COPIES OF THIS MESSAGE TO ANYONE YOU FEEL IT AFFECTS OR ANYONE
> WHO YOU WOULD LIKE TO HAVE COMMENT ON IT.
> 
> I would like to take a shot at adding undelete functionality to the ext2
> filesystem.  Since I've never done anything with the ext2fs before, I want
> to clear the design-plan with you before I actually do anything.  If it
> turns out that my design is inappropriate because I don't really understand
> ext2fs, please let me know!  If the design could be improved, please let me
> know that, too.  Finally, let me know if you think I should butt out and
> leave stuff like this to the experts.
> 
> 
> DESIGN GOALS:
> 
>   - should be able to undelete files without unmounting the filesystem
>   - undeletion should be selectable on a per-file basis
>   - undeletion should not require the user to learn extra programs
>     (I think we can do much better than MS-DOS style undeletion)
>   - make the system administrator's job as easy as possible
>   - don't create any security holes or make ext2fs less stable
>   - don't interfere with ext2fs compression, ACLs, or user quotas
> 
>   * undeletable deleted files and directories are treated the same as normal
>     files and directories, except that the space they use can be reclaimed by
>     the filesystem when needed.  The undeletable deleted files are stored in an
>     "undelete" directory which can be viewed by the user using "ls".  The user
>     can then undelete a file by "mv"ing it to its original location or by
>     keeping the deleted file in the "undelete" directory and making a copy of
>     it with "cp", "cat", "dd", or any other Unix utility.
> 
> 
> FILE ATTRIBUTES:
> 
>   Each file should have a set of "attribute" bits.  For example, this set
>   would contain one bit to indicate whether the file is automatically
>   compressed by ext2fs and another bit to indicate whether the file should
>   be undeletable.
> 
>   As far as I can tell, the i_flags field of the ext2_inode is currently not
>   used and could be used to hold the file's attribute bits.
> 
>   When a file is created, it inherits a copy of the attribute bits of its
>   parent directory.
> 
>   A new system call, sys_chattr( char *pathname, unsigned long attr ), would
>   be implemented to change the attributes of a file which already exists.  A
>   new program, chattr, would be written to change the attribute bits on a file
>   and would function in the same way as chmod from the GNU fileutils package.
> 
>   The stat system call would be modified to copy the attribute bits for a file
>   or directory from the inode to the new_stat structure.  The __unused5 field
>   would be changed to st_attr.  This means that ordinary programs, such as ls,
>   can determine what attribute bits are set for a file.
> 
>   ls (also from the GNU fileutils package) would be changed so that it will
>   display a file's attribute bits to the left of the file's permission bits
>   if the -e flag is set.
> 
>   mv and cp would be changed to handle the attribute bits correctly, if
>   necessary.
>   
> 
> UNDELETE DIRECTORY TABLE INODE:
> 
>   The purpose of the undelete directory table inode is to allow each user to
>   have their own undelete directory for a partition wherever they want on that
>   partition.  This allows deleted files to be manipulated in the same manner
>   as normal files but without allowing users to see the names, sizes (and
>   possibly contents) of deleted files belonging to other users.
> 
>   A special inode (inode 6, for example) is set aside for the undelete
>   directory table (udt).  The udt will be accessed through a system call that
>   the VFS will dispatch to the ext2 filesystem as a "miscellaneous superblock 
>   operation".  ext2fs will then do one of several operations based on the
>   arguments (lookup, change, add, delete a udt entry).
> 
>   Several fields of this inode are used for special purposes:
> 	i_flags		--> system undelete directory inode #
> 	i_mode		--> minimum uid in table
> 	i_uid		--> maximum uid in table
> 	i_gid		--> default action: delete or move to system undeldir
> 
>   The blocks pointed to by the directory table inode contain an udt_entry for
>   each user, sorted in order of increasing uid:
> 	struct udt_entry {
> 	  unsigned short uid;
> 	  unsigned short reserved;  /* for future expansion: pass variable? */
> 	  unsigned long  inode;     /* points to user's undelete directory */
> 	  unsigned long  reserved2; /* for future expansion: undelete quota? */
>         };
>   A value of zero in the inode field means that all files for that user should
>   be deleted permanently instead of being saved for undeletion.
> 
>   Each block pointed to by the special undelete inode has the following
>   structure:
> 
> 	#define EXT2_UDT_ENTRIES(s) \
> 	  (( EXT2_BLOCKSIZE(s) - sizeof( struct udt_block_header )) /  \
> 	  sizeof( struct udt_entry ));
> 
> 	struct udt_block_header {
> 	  unsigned short   max_uid;   /* Highest uid stored in this block */
> 	  unsigned short   uid_count; /* Number of uids stored in this block */
> 	};
> 
> 	struct udt_block {
> 	  struct udt_block_header header;
> 	  struct udt_entry entry[1]; /* Size of array depends on blocksize */
> 	};
> 
>   In order to "delete" files or automatically purge "deleted" files (when more
>   space is needed), the kernel needs to look up users in the undelete directory
>   table.  However, this lookup should never be too bad.  First, only users who
>   can create and delete files on a filesystem should be in the filesystem's
>   udt; everyone else will use the system undelete directory for that
>   filesystem.  Second, for most systems a single block of entries in the udt
>   should be sufficient for everybody on the system:  with a blocksize of 1024,
>   there are 85 udt entries per block (341 entries per block if the blocksize is
>   4096).  (If it turns out systems need more than two blocks of udt entries,
>   I can add an index block to the implementation for those systems).  Within
>   a single block, a binary search is used to find an entry.
> 
>   The system administrator can configure the default treatment of deleted files
>   whose owner is not in the udt on a per-partition basis (see i_gid field
>   above). On the other hand, if the user IS in the udt but there is a problem
>   with the undelete directory inode# for that user (inode not in use, not a
>   directory, etc.), the system undelete directory will be used.
> 
>   A special program, udt, manages the directory table:
> 	udt -p [user...]		Print name of user's undelete directory
> 	udt -r user			Remove user from table
> 	udt -a user dir			Add or change a user in the table
> 	udt -c				Check table
>   The last form, "udt -c", check to be sure that the entries in the table are
>   sorted correctly, that the undelete directories exist and are actually
>   directories, etc..  In general, it performs all the checks that e2fsck
>   performs on the undelete directory table, but it also checks the
>   undelete directory table against /etc/passwd and issue warnings if there
>   are any users that listed in one file that are not in the other.  In general,
>   only root will be able to run udt, although normal users will be able to
>   do a "udt -p" on themselves.
> 
>   
> DELETING A FILE:
> 
>   namei.c:ext2_unlink() is the function we want to modify in order to support
>   undeletion.
> 
>   Before calling ext2_delete_entry(), lookup the undeletion directory for the
>   file's owner
> 
>   If the inode# of the undeletion directory is the same as the inode number of
>   the parent directory the file we want to delete, it means that the file has
>   already been deleted and we are being asked to make the deletion permanent so
>   go ahead and do the deletion the way we do it now.
> 
>   Otherwise, append ASCII inode# of the file to the file's name and call
>   ext2_rename() to move the "deleted" file to the user's undelete directory.
> 
> 
> RECLAIMING SPACE USED BY DELETED (BUT UNDELETABLE) FILES:
> 
>   To purge all deleted files that were deleted more than a week ago:
>     find UNDELETE_DIRECTORY -mindepth 1 -ctime +7 -exec rm \{\} \;
> 
>   balloc.c:ext2_new_block():~440 -- add code to try to free up some blocks by
>   deleting files in the user's undelete directory.
> 
>   ialloc.c:ext2_new_inode():~410 -- add code to try to get more inodes by
>   deleting files in the user's undelete directory.
> 
> 
> EXAMPLE:
> 
>   $ whoami
>   john
>   $ udt -p
>   /home/john/deleted_files	<--- set up by the system administrator
>   $ ls -la ~john/deleted_files
>   drwx------   2 john   users        1024 Jun 11 22:58 .
>   drwxr-xr-x  30 john   users        1024 Jul 16 09:13 ..
>   $ echo "foo" > foo
>   $ ls -lie foo
>     5955 -u -rwxr-xr-x  1 john    users         4 Aug 13 12:25 foo
>   --->   ^^ -e flag willdisplay attributes: 1st bit compression, 2nd undelete
>   $ rm foo
>   $ ls -lie ~john/deleted_files
>     5955 -u -rwxr-xr-x  1 john    users         4 Aug 13 12:25 foo.5955
>   $ echo "foo again" > foo ; rm foo ; ls -lie ~john/deleted_files
>     5955 -u -rwxr-xr-x  1 john    users         4 Aug 13 12:25 foo.5955
>     5957 -u -rwxr-xr-x  1 john    users        10 Aug 13 12:26 foo.5957
>   $ mv ~john/deleted_files/foo.5955 foo    <--- THIS UNDELETES THE FILE
>   $ ls -lie foo
>     5955 -u -rwxr-xr-x  1 john    users         4 Aug 13 12:25 foo
>   $ cat foo
>   foo
> 
> 
> 
> DISADVANTAGES:
> 
>   - directory heirarchy is not preserved for deleted files: users must decide
>     in which directory they want to put an deleted file when they undelete it.
> 
>   - the undelete directory table makes the implementation more compilcated and
>     slower than other undelete implementations might.
> 
> 
> ADVANTAGES:
> 
>   - no special program is needed to undelete files
> 
>   - system administrator can set up the undelete director(y|ies) in many
>     different ways depending on security needs and personal prefferences
> 
> 
> NOTES:
> 
>   - Right now, I don't see enough reasons to use dtime.  ctime could be
>     modified when a file is deleted and then used to determine which deleted
>     file to purge when more space is needed.
> 
>   - could add "fair" round-robin method of freeing blocks from other user's
>     deleted files by adding a "pass" variable to the udt_entry.
> 
>   - could add "undelete quota" -- maximum # of blocks that a user could have
>     of deleted files.  When deleting an undeletable file, read inodes of
>     all files in undelete directory and sum the sizes.  If size of new
>     file to delete + sizes of old deleted files is greater than the undelete
>     quota (stored in the user's udt entry), start purging the deleted files
>     until the new one will fit.  If the new file is itself bigger than the
>     quota then it will be permanently deleted rather than saved for undeletion.
> 
> 
> Please let me know what you think.  If you approve, I'll go ahead and try to
> implement undeletion the way I've outlined it above.
> 
> Thank you for your consideration!
> 
> 		Mark Montague
> 		plph@umcc.umich.edu
> 


