Cecilia,

I know Katie wrote to you a while back with the decision we had decided 
to go with an in-house email system for our alums for now.  I'm writing 
with some of the details.

While the Athena proposal was attractive, and we believe we will move in 
its direction in a few years, at the moment we'd prefer to "get our feet 
wet" with a basic email service with low initial costs to both ourselves 
and those who subscribe to the service.

We plan on setting up a Macintosh-based email and bbs system using the 
FirstClass software package from SoftArc.  This system supports both 
dial-up and network users, with accessibility from Mac and Windows 
clients and via terminal emulation.  We would initially install 4 analog 
lines for the alums and AppleTalk clients on our Mac network for our 
staff and our alums.  I have heard good things about the package on 
various listserv groups I subscribe to, and the Boston Computer 
Society's Mac user group recently switched to FirstClass as its system.  

One FirstClass option we would like to install is PostalUnion Deluxe, an 
Internet email gateway between the FirstClass system and Internet.  For 
this we would equip the gateway Mac (probably a IIcx) with an MITNet 
drop as the Internet side of the connection.  Is this okay?  I would not 
expect great amount of traffic from this - the only traffic FirstClass 
generates is email - but thought it necessary to check with you before 
we purchase the setup.  The gateway is very stable - Information 
Electronics (who wrote the gateway) will provide us with references if 
we wish; they mentioned one site in Canada where their gateway is 
handling 20,000 pieces of mail per day.

On a separate note, we would also like to set up a Mac as an FTP/gopher 
server on the Internet for our alums already with Internet accounts to 
access documents from.  The package I would use is "ftpd" which is 
already in use at many sites -- the coordinators of several of the Mac 
mailing lists I belong to are now making shareware and other documents 
this using this package.  Again, I don't expect a big traffic load, just 
wanted to clear this with DCNS before we did anything....

We do expect to move to the Athena model in a few years.  But for now 
with our tight finances we can get this system up and running for under 
$5,000 and gain experience and a better sense of our market.

Thanks!  Look forward to hearing from you.

David Libby
Mac Consultant
MIT Alumni/ae Association

