Subject: [dmlibby@MIT.EDU (David M. Libby): Alumni/ae email/bbs system]

My first "gut" reaction is "Sounds like a good start." Although I am not
personally familiar with the FirstClass software, there are many successful
BBS systems in the world and as a result quite a few competent packages.
Perhaps more importantly, these packages are often designed to be easy to
use.

I believe that recent alumni will be underwhelmed and it will certainly not
be viewed as an alumni extension of Athena. On the other hand older (richer?)
alumni who are at best beginning computer users will have an easier time
then if the Alumni Office provided an Athena lookalike.

I like the idea of them operating a Gopher server. I am glad to see them
taking the initiative.

I do have some questions that I would like to ask.

How will alumni get registered to use this system?

Answer: I propose that all alumni have the ability to receive an account,
but only those who request one should in fact get one. It would be a *big*
mistake for them to create mailboxes for all alumni and then advertise
to other alumni that this was a good way to reach alumni. I, for one, would
not want a mailbox on that system to gather messages intended for me, that
I do not read!

How much manpower is the Alumni Office willing to devote to this?

Running a BBS can become a full time job, particularly if most users are
beginners. My suspicion is that the Alumni Office may well rise to the
challenge. I believe this because if nothing else it sounds like they
have the pride of ownership of this approach.

			-Jeff

