Cec - 

The Alumni/ae Association sounds enthusiastic about electronic 
communication for alums.  We should do everything we can to encourage 
them.

I see nothing particularly wrong with the approach they suggest.  
Michael Barrow has had direct experience with the BCS's systems, and 
thus can probably offer the most informed opinion.  I think that they 
underestimate the support costs of running such a system.

I believe that we should be able to offer a similar level of service at 
a lower cost.  For example a 4 line slip server, TechMail accounts,  
TechInfo, and NetNews, would seem to me to offer all they are proposing.  
While we should not discourage them from moving forward, we should 
encourage the use of larger, central, more cost effective, shared 
resources rather than lots of little servers all over the place.

There has been some discussion from time to time of IS managing an MIT 
wide distribution service, a single machine (mit-dist.mit.edu ?) which 
would be accessible via TechInfo, Gopher, FTP, AFS, etc.  I think that 
such a service would be useful to many groups at MIT, including the 
Alumni/ae Association.  

I feel strongly the extending MITnet to MIT alums should be a key part 
of our future plans and direction.  Perhaps we should offer to work with 
them in their experimental foray into cyberspace, and offer to pick up 
the tab for the first year.

- Mark
------------
Mark Curby             
MIT Network Services       MIT Room E40-342G
(617) 253-7725             77 Massachusetts Ave.
mlc@mit.edu                Cambridge, MA  02139

