*** EOOH ***
To: "Linux-Activists" <linux-activists@joker.cs.hut.fi>
From: Mitchum DSouza <m.dsouza%mrc-apu.cam.ac.uk@FINHUTC.hut.fi>
Subject:      Re: New Idea for Ldconfig
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1993 14:06:44 +0300



Excellent stuff David. I was just about to email you and ask if we were ever
going to revive this thread which was in deep hibernation. I can't believe
after 8 months that it has re-surfaced which more positive interest. I don't
think even bears hibernate that long.

>    From: David Engel <david@istwok.ods.com>
>    Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1993 00:39:53 +0300
>
>    As some of you know, I built two prototypes a while back of a shared
>    library version of the Linux dynamic linker called ld.so.  This type
>    of implementation has two main advantages.  First, the size of each
>    executable is reduced by ^2k because the loading/dynamic linking code
>    is no longer included.  Second, the loading/dynamic linking code can
>    be easily updated for all programs by simply installing a new version
>    of ld.so.
>
>
>    Anyway, while I was writing the manual page for my recently released
>    chlib utility (look for the announcement in c.o.l.a), a new idea
>    occurred to me.  Instead of building a cache to be read by ld.so, what
>    if ldconfig simply updated the appropriate symlink when a new library
>    was found?  Such an ldconfig could either be run automatically at boot
>    time, or on demand whenever new libraries are installed.  This would

Although this seem like a good idea, I think eventually having links pointing
to appropriate libraries will have to be phased out. Libraries updates will
have to be determined by the major and minor verison numbers and used to load
it automatically - hence libc.so.4.4.2 will automatically be loaded if
libc.so.4 was required by ignoring the major/minor no. which will only be used
to determine a more recent update. But then again how does one cope with
libraries without version numbers (although a "bad" thing some libraries
e.g. libemu - the dos emulator library - does this me thinks Bob ??)

>    be a much simpler implementation and would even be useful without
>    ld.so, although I still think ld.so is worth pursuing for the reasons
>    given above.
>

Definetly ld.so is the way to go for reasons above and those I hve explained
in the past. However what you didn't mention is that loading times will be a
bit longer as the loading stage requires reading from either a in memory cache
or having to open and read /etc/ld.so.cache to determine the latest version
whenever a shared binary is executed.

Can you explain the strategy for the cache building you implemented (if you
have) ?? The last time we spoke (emailed) it seems you were concerned with the
time required for reading the cache amongst other things.

Other points to ponder is whether the cache should be built dynamically
(deja-vu David :-) i.e.  without the need for executing ldconfig whenever a
new library(ies) are installed - this could be achieved by reading the
st_mtime on the trusted load directory paths comparing it with the
/etc/ld.so.cache and rebuilding if necessary. This is a step forward from
SunOS's ldconfig which requires the cache to be built manually, however as
you guessed the load time for the first binary to be executed after a new
library is installed, (probably the command `ls' i guess), will be slightly
longer as we will have to fork the ldconfig program and then renew the in
memory cache.  However I have no reservations against this as it is a
zillion times better that installing new DLL's and then maually relinking
each of libm, libc..... Surely the automatic cache rebuild will be quicker
and less error prone (How many times have we all seen the "Help: trashed my
libc.so.4 link" in the newsgroups).

Way to go David !!

Mitch




