*** EOOH ***
From: dcctdw@Athena.MIT.EDU
To: summer-fun@Athena.MIT.EDU, sipb-soc@Athena.MIT.EDU
Cc: wes@Athena.MIT.EDU
Subject: The Other Side
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 93 12:39:10 EDT

Entrance is normally $7; for groups > 25 (i think), it's $3.
There are 6 major attractions inside, each cost $3.

There isn't a lot to do beside the 6 attractions, and with it being $3 a
pop, you don't want to go unless you've gotten the $3 entrance fee.  I went
on 3 of the attractions; they were worth $2, but it's really debateable if
they were worth $3 (since they're all so short).

1: Virtuality #1
	This simulator has a helmet, waist-ring, and gun.  The idea is that
you wander about a series of planes (think 3-D chessboard) blasting various
objects and/or other people.  I didn't try this, although i've seen it
before.  Duration is probably 4 minutes.  Either people were clueless, or
it's easy to confuse the controls...

2: Freedom 6
	This is a OMNIMAX film, although it's something puny like an eighth
screen or something -- it doesn't do sensory flooding like a real OMNIMAX
(a big minus IMHO).  The seats are bolted down onto a platform which moves;
it's basically a different angle of doing Star Tours.  I went on this; it
was OK.  (I got bothered a lot by the fact that you bounce off walls a lot
and don't explode; that, and the film has a few discontinuities, or at
least, your ship somehow does these really amazing 135' turns.)  Duration
is probably 6 minutes; it was hard to tell.

3: Virtuality #2
	You can either pilot a hang glider (didn't try it) or a biplane.
Nothing moves; the helmet allows you (like the first Virtuality) to look in
any direction.  Response ain't so good; if you quickly twist your head, you
can hear the computer saying "GIMME THAT GODDAMN PAGE I NEED IT NOW!".  If
you pan slowly, it's ok.  It's OK for $3, even though the biplane controls
are a little screwy -- if you get shot up a lot, rather than crashing and
getting a new set of wings, it seems you just get grounded and can't do a
lot.  Duration about 4 minutes.

4: Chameleon
	Setup: 2 pods opposite each other on a centrifuge.  Simulation:
race car driving.  You go fast, the pods orient such that you're pressed
back; you go into a turn, you feel the g-forces, blah blah blah.  Note that
it's 2 people per pod, so one person (the first person who gets in) does
the steering and gas; the other person is there mostly for the ride (he
controls the forward/reverse singleton gear).  Something really screwy --
the screen is sufficiently large -and- close that the driver is at a
definate angle -- makes driving in a straight line difficult.  Duration
about 2 minutes -- it's over fast!  

5: Reactor
	Ever been on Star Tours?  Exactly the same thing.  I didn't go on
this, since I've been on Star Tours myself.  A twist on this is that
individual seats move, rather than the whole cabin.  I heard that having
the whole cabin move is more realistic (even though, relativistically
speaking, they're equivalent i think...)  Unclear what duration is: my
guess is 6 minutes or so.

6: Somethingorother
	This is interesting to watch, but i certainly wouldn't pay money.
It's essentially interactive TV -- you sit in front of a camera, and
there's a TV in front of you.  Displayed behind the on-screen you is, say,
a soccer net.  Soccer balls now start flying in; you flap your arms around,
and if your on-screen arms hit the on-screen ball, the on-screen ball does
the proverbial on-screen (yes, i'm being silly; sue me) bouncing away.
There are a variety of options (make your own video; play with bouncing a
ball around; the soccer frob; i think there are 3 others).  No clue what
duration is; i'd guess 4-6 minutes.

There are also various arcade games in there and a few Macs displaying
something or other.  There's a continuous laser show (it's mostly for mob
pleasing, i think, but it's still kinda neat) and videos of computer
animation (a lot of which looks a lot like the stuff done at the AI Leg
Lab).  It's cute.  The arcade games are mostly boring; the few cool ones
have controls which are sufficiently ill-defined as to make them difficult
to play (it's hard to maneuver accurately in 3D with only 2 controls).
Most games are 50c to play.

Lines aren't short -- expect 45-60 minute waits if you arrive around 6.
After 8, the lines shorten dramatically.  Food is available inside for
probably exorbitant prices (I didn't check).  No readmittance, so grab food
at South Station before you come (there's a McBread, McD, and Sbarro's,
among other things).  There's a shuttle which you can take for free from
South Station -- as you come out of South Station, across the street to the
right-ish is a black stone circle and a black box.  The bus stops in front
of that.  If the driver stops at the front of the WTC, go down the
escalators; if he drives past the escalators and goes to the traffic
circle, backtrack blahblahblah.  Note that TOC is not actually inside the
WTC, but across the street.  The show closes at 10:30pm; they are closed
today for a private audience.

So, for $12, you can see 3 of the events.  Is it worth 2 movies?  Heh,
well, that depends on what movies you want to see, but my guess is
"probably not, unless you have a real job".  It seems that what really
needs to happen is a Media scum needs to link up with a M.E. jock and start
making a ludicrous amount of money...

Oh, and if you're Wes Carroll (who, curiously enough, is not on either of
these lists), you'd probably enjoy the amazing speaker setup they have,
which is synced to the laser show.  Amazing bass output.  You could just
-feel- the C# D# F# G# F# bass line in "Danger Zone" (from Top Gun)...  way
cool.  :> !

dave

