        hjl@nynexst.com, alfie@dcs.warwick.ac.uk
In-Reply-To: <9308180140.AA22978@tsx-11.MIT.EDU> from "Theodore Ts'o" at Aug 17, 93 09:40:23 pm
X-Mailer: ELM [version 2.4 PL21]
Content-Type: text
Content-Length: 3514      

X-Mn-Key: GCC

> Was there some reason why this never got adopted for general use within
> Linux?  From your description, it sounds like a big win, and it's
> something that could be easily phased in --- all you need to do is
> widely disseminate the /lib/ld.so, and then supply a new crt0 for people
> to use which references it.

Enough people expressed interest in seeing a more complete package
including an ldconfig that I agreed to look into it.  It just took me
longer than expected. :-)  I just finished a two month long crunch at
work to get our latest release ready, so I should have more time to 
spend on Linux-related projects -- for a while, anyway.

Before ld.so goes public, however, there are a couple of things that
need to be handled.  First, the startup code should probably be
changed to load ld.so using mmap instead of uselib.  This would allow
ld.so to be unloaded using munmap since it's only needed at startup.
Second, in addition to the DLL code, which uses a BSD-style copyright,
ld.so also includes some functions lifted from the Linux kernel, which
are GPL'd.  Either the DLL authors need to allow their code to be
GPL'd, or Linus needs to let us use his code with a less restrictive
copyright.

There is also one other change, which I feel is highly desirable, but
could probably wait for a future version.  That is to provide some
mechanism for a configurable, default LD_LIBRARY_PATH.  We all know
this can't be done securely with environment variables but could be
done with a root-owned file (/etc/ld.so.conf?).  An implementation
involving shared memory might also be possible, but I don't know
enough about that to know if could be made secure.

> Sounds like a good idea; it would certainly be more automatic than your
> chlib program.

That's my feeling also.  The chlib idea was a real quickie I got after
reading the recent batch of messages in c.o.l about accidentally
deleted links.  Since I'd already written and tested it when I got the
new idea, I decided to release it anyway.

Before I begin reworking my current ldconfig, however, I need some
input on the following issue:

I originally envisioned ldconfig scanning the specified directories
and creating all symlinks in a single directory, /lib by default.
However, this can be problematic for systems that mount libraries with
NFS.  For example, if the administrator on a system that exports its
/usr partition upgrades a library, runs ldconfig locally and then
deletes the old library, every system that imports /usr would then
have a symlink to a nonexistent library.  I know this particular
scenario could be avoided by properly educating administrators, but
I'm not sure how effective that would be, especially with the growing
number of Unix-newbies Linux is attracting.

Another approach, which makes some sense to me, is for ldconfig to
only create symlinks in the directory where a library is found.  This
ensures that if the link is available, the library itself is also
available.  The downside is that all directories which contain
libraries need to be in LD_LIBRARY_PATH.  For our current needs, a
default path of /usr/X386/lib, /usr/lib and /lib would probably
suffice.  In the long run, however, this approach would require the
flexibility of a configurable, default path like the one mentioned
above.

Comments?

David
