Subject: [ANNOUNCE] The NYS Project: Need DNS/Hesiod hacker
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1993 18:02:49 +0300

*** EOOH ***
To: "Linux-Activists" <linux-activists@joker.cs.hut.fi>
From: linux-announce@TC.Cornell.EDU (Matt Welsh)
Subject: [ANNOUNCE] The NYS Project: Need DNS/Hesiod hacker
Date: Wed, 18 Aug 1993 18:02:49 +0300


Path: bounce-bounce
Newsgroups: comp.os.linux.announce
From: pen@lysator.liu.se (Peter Eriksson)
Subject: The NYS Project: Need DNS/Hesiod hacker
Organization: Lysator ACS at Linkoping University
Keywords: NYS, NIS, YP, TCP/IP, networking, development
Reply-To: pen@lysator.liu.se (Peter Eriksson)
Followup-To: comp.os.linux
Approved: linux-announce@tc.cornell.edu (Matt Welsh)

(NYS? Yeah, I know, it's a boring name but what the heck.)

NYS is a project developing a free (Library GPL) client-side
implementation of NIS+ (NIS version 3), YP (NIS version 2) and DNS/Hesiod
access for a number of /etc "maps" (passwd, group, shadow, hosts, services,
rpc, protocols, networks, netgroup, netmasks, ethers, bootparams, aliases,
timezone and possibly others too...). All thru a name services "switch"
ala Solaris 2 /etc/nsswitch.conf.

(Yes, I know there exists another client side implementation of YP for Linux
which I believe has been ported from 386BSD? Anyway, it's more fun to write
things from scratch and I want more functionality than just YP :-)

Current status of NYS is that the Nsswitch code is written and working
(can be improved of course, but that's a later issue), the YP and NIS+
low level access code is written. (The NIS+ code will be modified slightly
to be more call-level compatible with Suns Solaris 2 when I have time).
The YP map handling code (that parses the replies) is being worked on.
NIS+ also. But more help is always welcome...

But it would be great if someone experienced with Hesiod/DNS could help
out with the DNS part of the project.

Please get in touch with me if you're interrested and have the knowledge
so things can be coordinated.

The current sources of the project can be FTP'd from ftp.lysator.liu.se
in the directory pub/linux/NYS as (nys-0.*.tar.gz, where * is a moving
target :-)

You probably need the latest 4.4.2 libraries and Gcc 2.4.5 or later to
be able to run this code without experiencing coredumps or so.

And there exists no documentation whatsoever, so UTSL.

/Peter




