Subject: ext2 undelete proposal (fwd)

*** EOOH ***
From: sct@dcs.ed.ac.uk
Date: Thu, 19 Aug 93 01:06:42 BST
To: Mark Montague <plph@umcc.umich.edu>
Cc: sct@dcs.ed.ac.uk, tytso@Athena.MIT.EDU, Remy.Card@masi.ibp.fr
In-Reply-To: Remy CARD's message of Mon, 16 Aug 1993 21:13:33 +0100 (BST) <199308162016.AA17925@masi.ibp.fr>
Subject: ext2 undelete proposal (fwd)

Hi Mark,

I've just received a copy of your undelete proposals from Remy.  They
do appear very well thought out, but a few detailed comments follow...

>> PLEASE FORWARD COPIES OF THIS MESSAGE TO ANYONE YOU FEEL IT AFFECTS OR ANYONE
>> WHO YOU WOULD LIKE TO HAVE COMMENT ON IT.

Yes please!

>> I would like to take a shot at adding undelete functionality to the
>> ext2 filesystem.  Since I've never done anything with the ext2fs
>> before, I want to clear the design-plan with you before I actually
>> do anything.  If it turns out that my design is inappropriate
>> because I don't really understand ext2fs, please let me know!  If
>> the design could be improved, please let me know that, too.

Will do...

>> Finally, let me know if you think I should butt out and leave stuff
>> like this to the experts.

Huh?  That's never been the Linux way - Linux is the method we use to
become experts!

>> DESIGN GOALS:
>> 
>>   - should be able to undelete files without unmounting the
>>   filesystem
>>   - undeletion should be selectable on a per-file basis
Definitely.
>>   - undeletion should not require the user to learn extra programs
>>     (I think we can do much better than MS-DOS style undeletion)
I'm not entirely sure about this; a single new 'undelete' command is
not necessarily a bad thing.
>>   - make the system administrator's job as easy as possible
Yup.
>>   - don't create any security holes or make ext2fs less stable
Number one priority here.  Absolutely.
>>   - don't interfere with ext2fs compression, ACLs, or user quotas
That's the ext2fs philosophy - lots of capability, totally integrated.

>>   * undeletable deleted files and directories are treated the same as normal
>>     files and directories, except that the space they use can be reclaimed by
>>     the filesystem when needed.  The undeletable deleted files are stored in an
>>     "undelete" directory which can be viewed by the user using "ls".  The user
>>     can then undelete a file by "mv"ing it to its original location or by
>>     keeping the deleted file in the "undelete" directory and making a copy of
>>     it with "cp", "cat", "dd", or any other Unix utility.

I assume you mean some top level /undeleted directory akin to
/lost+found, rather than a separate /undeleted directory in each
normal directory or for each user.

I think we have to think carefully about the overall philosophy here -
do we want undeleted files to be hidden but easily recovered, or
should it be completely user-open as you suggest?  There are arguments
on both sides.  In particular, how do you propose to resolve name
conflicts in /undeleted for multiple deletions of files with the same
name, either in the same or in different directories?  Do you propose
to record the source directory of the deleted files with each one?
Having an invisible directory of undeleted files can resolve these
questions, but the user would have to learn a new undelete tool to
access such a directory.  Heck, the user will *have* to learn at least
one new tool anyway, if only to set up the per-file and per-directory
undelete parameters.

>> FILE ATTRIBUTES:
>> 
>>   Each file should have a set of "attribute" bits.  For example,
>>   this set would contain one bit to indicate whether the file is
>>   automatically compressed by ext2fs and another bit to indicate
>>   whether the file should be undeletable.
>> 
>>   As far as I can tell, the i_flags field of the ext2_inode is
>>   currently not used and could be used to hold the file's attribute
>>   bits.
>> 
>>   When a file is created, it inherits a copy of the attribute bits
>>   of its parent directory.

Done.  This is exactly the way I'm doing file marking for the
compressed filesystem, and I have redefined the flags field to be a
bitfield struct to achieve this.  There is loads of free space in that
struct for undelete flags.

>>   A new system call, sys_chattr( char *pathname, unsigned long attr
>>   ), would be implemented to change the attributes of a file which
>>   already exists.  A new program, chattr, would be written to
>>   change the attribute bits on a file and would function in the
>>   same way as chmod from the GNU fileutils package.

We need a new program, yes; I was thinking more of 'e2set' or 'e2attr'
as a suitable name for such an ext2fs-specific utility.  However, I
don't like the idea of cluttering the kernel with fs-specific kernel
calls; much better to just hack on another ioctl() for ext2fs files.
The ioctl indirection is already there in the vfs layer.

>>   The stat system call would be modified to copy the attribute bits
>>   for a file or directory from the inode to the new_stat structure.
>>   The __unused5 field would be changed to st_attr.  This means that
>>   ordinary programs, such as ls, can determine what attribute bits
>>   are set for a file.

ioctl again - the third ioctl argument can be a struct address into
which the kernel can copy results as well as read them.

>>   ls (also from the GNU fileutils package) would be changed so that
>>   it will display a file's attribute bits to the left of the file's
>>   permission bits if the -e flag is set.

Possible, although I am a trifle reluctant to polute standard GNU
tools with fs-specific code.  I would rather have a separate set of
ext2fs tools at first, and to try to integrate them into the fileutils
only after they have proven stable.

>>   mv and cp would be changed to handle the attribute bits
>>   correctly, if necessary.

Yup, as above.

>> UNDELETE DIRECTORY TABLE INODE:
>> 
>>   The purpose of the undelete directory table inode is to allow
>>   each user to have their own undelete directory for a partition
>>   wherever they want on that partition.  This allows deleted files
>>   to be manipulated in the same manner as normal files but without
>>   allowing users to see the names, sizes (and possibly contents) of
>>   deleted files belonging to other users.
>> 
>>   A special inode (inode 6, for example) is set aside for the
>>   undelete directory table (udt).  The udt will be accessed through
>>   a system call that the VFS will dispatch to the ext2 filesystem
>>   as a "miscellaneous superblock operation".  ext2fs will then do
>>   one of several operations based on the arguments (lookup, change,
>>   add, delete a udt entry).
>> 
>>   Several fields of this inode are used for special purposes:
>> 	i_flags		--> system undelete directory inode #
>> 	i_mode		--> minimum uid in table
>> 	i_uid		--> maximum uid in table
>> 	i_gid		--> default action: delete or move to system
>> 			    undeldir

These flags can easily be placed in the superblock, where there is
*loads* of free space.  It's much more natural for them to be there.

Now, you are proposing to have per-user undeleted directories; why not
just have a single /undeleted directory, with mode 1777?  If we
prohibit file creation in this directory (easy enough to do), then
this still lets users rename or delete (permanently) files in that
directory.  We can also easily adapt the directory scanning routines
to pass over deleted file entries beloning to other users if we really
want to.  It does increase the chances of name conflicts, but that is
going to be a problem anyway.

Secondly, what we are talking about here is basically a per-user
filesystem database.  This is exactly what we need to implement
quotas.  (The existing Linux quota patches aren't quite sufficient;
they can't see holes for a start, and they aren't designed to work
with undeleting filesystems!)  Bearing this in mind, maybe we should
consider this right now, and design a user database which is at least
capable of being easily (and compatibly) expanded to accomodate extra
information such as quotas.

We might even want to place separate real and undeleted quotas for
each user, or a combined real+undeleted quota (so that the system
could automatically purge deleted files once this is exceeded).

>>   namei.c:ext2_unlink() is the function we want to modify in order to support
>>   undeletion.

Yup!

>>   Before calling ext2_delete_entry(), lookup the undeletion directory for the
>>   file's owner
>> 
>>   If the inode# of the undeletion directory is the same as the inode number of
>>   the parent directory the file we want to delete, it means that the file has
>>   already been deleted and we are being asked to make the deletion permanent so
>>   go ahead and do the deletion the way we do it now.
>> 
>>   Otherwise, append ASCII inode# of the file to the file's name and call
>>   ext2_rename() to move the "deleted" file to the user's undelete
>>   directory.

Remember to check for i_count = 1!  We don't want to make an undelete
record of files which are still in the filesystem (or do we?).

>> RECLAIMING SPACE USED BY DELETED (BUT UNDELETABLE) FILES:
>> 
>>   To purge all deleted files that were deleted more than a week ago:
>>     find UNDELETE_DIRECTORY -mindepth 1 -ctime +7 -exec rm \{\} \;
>> 
>>   balloc.c:ext2_new_block():~440 -- add code to try to free up some blocks by
>>   deleting files in the user's undelete directory.
>> 
>>   ialloc.c:ext2_new_inode():~410 -- add code to try to get more inodes by
>>   deleting files in the user's undelete directory.

Sounds about right.

>> DISADVANTAGES:
>> 
>>   - directory heirarchy is not preserved for deleted files: users
>>     must decide in which directory they want to put an deleted file
>>     when they undelete it.
>> 
>>   - the undelete directory table makes the implementation more
>>     compilcated and slower than other undelete implementations
>>     might.

Add namespace collision to the disadvantages, and it's potentially a
big one.

>> ADVANTAGES:
>> 
>>   - no special program is needed to undelete files
>> 
>>   - system administrator can set up the undelete director(y|ies) in many
>>     different ways depending on security needs and personal
>>     prefferences

This latter point is applicable even if we just keep a reserved list
of deleted files.

Add an extra advantage, by the way - users can view file contents
before deciding whether to undelete or purge them.  This is a pretty
useful feature!

>> NOTES:
>> 
>>   - Right now, I don't see enough reasons to use dtime.  ctime
>>     could be modified when a file is deleted and then used to
>>     determine which deleted file to purge when more space is
>>     needed.
>> 
>>   - could add "fair" round-robin method of freeing blocks from
>>     other user's deleted files by adding a "pass" variable to the
>>     udt_entry.
>> 
>>   - could add "undelete quota" -- maximum # of blocks that a user 
>>     could have of deleted files.  When deleting an undeletable
>>     file, read inodes of all files in undelete directory and sum
>>     the sizes.  If size of new file to delete + sizes of old
>>     deleted files is greater than the undelete quota (stored in the
>>     user's udt entry), start purging the deleted files until the
>>     new one will fit.  If the new file is itself bigger than the
>>     quota then it will be permanently deleted rather than saved for
>>     undeletion.

Definitely.  I would like to see integrated quota support here - it's
the obvious place to put it.

>> Please let me know what you think.  If you approve, I'll go ahead
>> and try to implement undeletion the way I've outlined it above.

I like it, but I think it's worth discussing the relative merits of
the in-filesystem versus reserved-directory approaches for maintaining
the lists of deleted files.

Cheers,
 Stephen.
--
Stephen Tweedie <sct@uk.ac.ed.dcs>   (Internet: <sct@dcs.ed.ac.uk>)
Department of Computer Science, Edinburgh University, Scotland.

