Eric:
> [ description of QMAGIC file type ]
> 
> 	How do people feel about this?  Unfortunately newer binaries will not
> run on older kernels once we start to switch over - perhaps the move to make
> would be to get the patches in the kernel ASAP and then switch over to make it
> less likely that people screw themselves.

I'm for it, but since it involves kernel changes, it's Linus'
decision.  I would like to see ld.so included in the next libc
release, but I suppose it could wait if that's what people want.

BTW, does any of the ld.so stuff interfere with your ELF efforts?

Linus:
> > Before ld.so goes public, however, there are a couple of things that
> > need to be handled.  First, the startup code should probably be
> > changed to load ld.so using mmap instead of uselib.  This would allow
> > ld.so to be unloaded using munmap since it's only needed at startup.
> 
> Note that there is no "mmap() instead of uselib()" - uselib() is as of
> pl12 just an interface to mmap() that does the open, code checks, mmap()
> and close.  So you can use munmap() on the uselib()'ed library, and
> using uselib() might result in smaller startup code (it also allows
> varying formats for the ld.so library once other formats than a.out are
> implemented). 

OK, I was aware that uselib now used mmap internally, but I wasn't
aware that a uselib could be undone with munmap.  Hmm, I just looked
at sys_munmap and there is one complication.  There is no way for the
startup code to know how much memory to munmap without opening the
file and reading the header.  If it has to do that, it might as well
do the mmap directly.

Now, there is not an immediate need to unmap ld.so.  With the current
implementation, not unmapping ld.so would only waste one page per
process.  I do expect that to grow, however, when/if we try to do more
sophistocated things.

> > Second, in addition to the DLL code, which uses a BSD-style copyright,
> > ld.so also includes some functions lifted from the Linux kernel, which
> > are GPL'd.  Either the DLL authors need to allow their code to be
> > GPL'd, or Linus needs to let us use his code with a less restrictive
> > copyright.
> 
> Post it and we'll see..  I don't see any real reason not to ok it. 

The only files I'm using are printk.c, vsprintf.c and ctype.c.  The
formatted I/O functions in libc would bring in to much excess baggage.

Ted:
> Fortunately, Linus has indicated that he doesn't see a problem with
> this, so we should be all right.

I didn't expect there would be a problem.  It did have to be addressed
nevertheless.

> better.  Although the mere fact that we've factored out the shared
> library loading code into ld.so means that if anyone wants to change the
> default LD_LIBRARY_PATH, they could just recompile and replace ld.so ---

That would work.

>    Another approach, which makes some sense to me, is for ldconfig to
>    only create symlinks in the directory where a library is found.
> 
> I would use this approach; if there are other directories where people
> want to have libraries, they can either customize ld.so (or
> /etc/ld.so.conf in the future), or they can create symlinks of
> libfoofah.so.1.3 to one of the standard lib directories, and then let
> ldconfig do the right thing.

OK, unless I hear strong objections, that's how this first version
will work.  I have relatives coming in tonight for a couple of days,
I'll try to have a test version ready this weekend.

David
