I agree with everyone else in saying that this is a good start. I have not
used the Mac BBS extensively from the admin end, but from a user
perspective it is an excellent system. They have the Postal Union gateway
installed and it transfers email & Usenet news (receive-only) to and from
the BCS hub via UUCP. Then the BCS Hub transfers email, etc. to the
Internet via UUCP through UUNET Technologies. All in all, the system works
quite well.

My only concern about this project is that they are underestimating the
amount of time needed to set up and maintain this system. Have they thought
about whether or not they will backup people's email? What kind of service
expectation are they going to provide? Etc, etc, etc....

I also don't know too much about the ftpd that runs on the Mac. If Dave
says that other people are using it successfully, then that's OK. I usually
believe that Unix machines are _really_ good for server-class machines,
especially since they don't crash! At least not usually! :-)

I have one final question: what's going to cost them $5000?

-- mlb

