David:
> > Other points to ponder is whether the cache should be built dynamically
> > (deja-vu David :-) i.e.  without the need for executing ldconfig whenever a
> > new library(ies) are installed - this could be achieved by reading the
> > st_mtime on the trusted load directory paths comparing it with the
> > /etc/ld.so.cache and rebuilding if necessary. This is a step forward ...
> 
> That's a little too ambitious right for me right now.  However, once
> we have an initial ld.so in place, we'll be able to experiment will
> all sorts of ideas, like yours, and have all programs take advantage
> of it by simply installing a new ld.so.
> 

Well its something to think about in the future anyway.

Brian Beuning:
> Call me a NEWBIE, but wouldn't it just be simpler to read the directory
> and figure out the newest version numbers.  On my sun, the /lib directory

It think the loading time degradation on a readdir() every time a binary needs
to be dynamically linked is too great a performance hit.

> and the /etc/ld.so.cache file are both 4096 bytes.  Either way, doesn't the
> data wind up staying in the disk block cache forever anyway and not needing
> a real disk read?

I think forever is a very strong word (like what you have to whisper when
getting married). No the cache is constantly being rebuilt.
As you mentioned the disk cache will ensure never having to perform a real
disk read until the cache is flushed. However the modification time
field in the stat structure can be queried as to when to perform a disk read
to get ldconfig to rebuild its own ld.so.cache. Even with the current
file systems linux has, the readdir() is sufficiently fast to enable a deamon
ldconfig process (very much like `update') to check and rebuild the cache on
the fly. However with NFS, bearing in mind our current 1024 rw block
implementation, it is necessary, in order to preserve file consistency across
server and clients, to have a very short lived file cache and subsequently
fairly expensive getattr calls will be required once the cache had expired.
Anyway i think this is a "far off" scenario and our priorities definetly lie
in the need to get ld.so and friends into standard distributions and onto
users disks.

David:
>    There is also one other change, which I feel is highly desirable, but
>    could probably wait for a future version.  That is to provide some
>    mechanism for a configurable, default LD_LIBRARY_PATH.  We all know
>    this can't be done securely with environment variables but could be
>    done with a root-owned file (/etc/ld.so.conf?).  

The configurable LD_LIBRARY_PATH is implemented by SunOS for e.g. by having
arguments to 'ldconfig' which augments the "trusted LD_LIBRARY_PATH". But yes
having this in a file for `ldconfig' to read is just as acceptable and would
save hardcoding paths into ld.so.

Ted:
> Again, sounds like a good idea; the less policy we mandate in ld.so, the
> better.  Although the mere fact that we've factored out the shared
> library loading code into ld.so means that if anyone wants to change the
> default LD_LIBRARY_PATH, they could just recompile and replace ld.so ---
> this is much better than what they would have needed to do in the past,
> which is to recompile every single binary on their system!

Full agreement there.

Eric:
...[explanation on forthcoming MAGIC headers deleted]....
>
> 	How do people feel about this?  Unfortunately newer binaries will not
> run on older kernels once we start to switch over - perhaps the move to make

I think most people will accept `forward compatability' as it implies 
natural progression to greater and better things. Clearly if I create a
QMAGIC executable and distribute it thereby forcing the user to upgrade his
kernel, I am doing him a favor - even though he may not percieve downloading
30 SLS disks over a 2400 modem line as being much of a favor. Definetly
breaking `backward compatability' - i.e. not being able to run old binaries
on new kernels, and forcing recompilation will cause the greatest upsets -
however HLu has indicated that this might be imminent when (if ??) we move to
glibc-1.06 proper.

> would be to get the patches in the kernel ASAP and then switch over to make it
> less likely that people screw themselves.

Yup this seems the way to go, way to go Eric :-)

Mitch

